	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Large-scale maize exports threaten local supplies of maize in South Africa</h1>

			
			<h4>
												27 December 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the CEO of Grain South Africa, Jannie de Villiers, a maize shortage is imminent in South Africa following large-scale exports of maize. South Africa has exported over 1.2 million tonnes of maize to Mexico, South Korea and Taiwan between May and November 2011. In addition, export sales have been made from grain still held in South African silos. This is ‘now causing panic among local buyers’, according to Mr de Villiers.</p><p>These maize exports were sold at an average price of R1,400 (€128) per tonne, but local prices in November 2011 were approaching R2,900 (€265) per tonne and were expected to exceed R3,000 (€275) per tonne by the end of the month.</p><p>A Ministry of Agriculture official said that the current situation was the product of ‘successful exports of maize by the private sector in recent months’, with South Africa experiencing a product of ‘market dynamics’.</p><p>The South African National Agricultural Marketing Council had previously proposed the establishment of an information system to monitor ‘import and export intentions’ for cereals, but this had been rejected by industry stakeholders.</p><p>The current situation on the South African market is likely to drive up maize prices to the detriment of the livestock sector in South Africa. The domestic maize supply situation needs to be seen against the background of rising international prices, following adverse weather conditions.</p><p>However, this also needs to be set against earlier press claims that South African farmers were set to plant more land to maize in the 2011/12 season (nearly 10% more) in response to higher prices. The South Africa Crop Estimates Committee (CEC) ‘expects South Africa to harvest 10,608 million tonnes of maize’ in 2010/11.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Thecropsite.com</i>, ‘Maize shortage, price spikes preventable’, 10 November 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thecropsite.com/news/9613/maize-shortage-price-spikes-preventable" target="_self">http://www.thecropsite.com/news/9613/maize-shortage-price-spikes-prevent...</a></p><p><i>Thecropsite.com</i>, ‘South Africa maize plantings seen up, wheat output down’, 26 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thecropsite.com/news/9483/south-africa-maize-plantings-seen-up-wheat-output-down" target="_self">http://www.thecropsite.com/news/9483/south-africa-maize-plantings-seen-u...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The current maize supply situation in South Africa contrasts sharply with the situation earlier in 2011. As late as July 2011, USDA was reported ‘a carry-over stock of approximately five million tonnes and a current crop of around 11 million tonnes’ (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Cereals/South-African-maize-production-down" target="_blank">South African maize production down</a>’, 6 October 2011). In February 2011, USDA had reported that stock levels were high enough to hold down local maize prices despite international maize price trends (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Cereals/Divergent-trends-within-South-Africa-s-cereals-sector" target="_blank">Divergent trends within South Africa’s cereals sector</a>’, 2 May 2011). This assisted the South African poultry sector in meeting intensifying competition from poultry meat imports from Brazil (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Poultry/Poultry-Focus/Trends-in-the-South-African-poultry-sector" target="_blank">Trends in the South African poultry sector</a>’, 12 November 2011).</p><p>However, the absence of a marketing information system to monitor exports, imports, stock levels, consumption trends and production forecasts has contributed to rapid increase in the local maize price, with local maize prices being unable to adjust in a timely manner to reduced stock levels.</p><p>This now leaves the South African livestock sector facing significantly higher feed prices. This is likely to undermine the competitiveness of South African poultry producers vis-à-vis imports of Brazilian, US and EU poultry meat products. This in turn is likely to increase pressure from the South African poultry industry for higher levels of tariff protection, particularly against imports of ‘dark meat’, which can be exported so long as the costs of transport are below the costs of alternative methods of disposal. Few markets exist for these cuts in OECD countries (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Poultry/Changing-patterns-in-Brazilian-poultry-exports-cause-concern-in-South-Africa" target="_blank">Changing patterns in Brazilian poultry exports cause concern in South Af...</a>’, 2 May 2011).</p><p>These developments highlight the perceived need for new types of policy tools (such as market information systems and statutory reporting requirements) to overcome market shortcomings and strengthen the functioning of domestic supply chains.</p>
		</div>
		
